    <div id="home" class="section active">
        <h1>Welcome to the Course</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <p>This interactive website covers the syllabus for <strong>Computer Security and Cyber Law</strong>. Use the navigation menu to study individual units, perform practical exercises, and test your knowledge with the final exam.</p>
            <h3>Course Highlights:</h3>
            <ul>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Cryptography:</strong> Classical ciphers, Symmetric vs Asymmetric, RSA, DES. [cite: 1]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Network Security:</strong> Firewalls, VPNs, IPSec, DMZ architecture. [cite: 2]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Authentication:</strong> Passwords, Biometrics, Kerberos, Digital Certificates. [cite: 3]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Cyber Law & Forensics:</strong> Investigation procedures, Evidence handling, Cyberbullying. [cite: 9, 10]</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit2" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 2: Cryptography & Algorithms</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>Key Concepts</h3>
            <ul>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Symmetric Key:</strong> Same key for encryption and decryption (e.g., DES, Caesar Cipher). [cite: 1]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Asymmetric Key:</strong> Different keys (Public/Private) for encryption and decryption (e.g., RSA). [cite: 1]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Classical Ciphers:</strong> Caesar (Shift), Playfair (Matrix), Rail Fence (Transposition). [cite: 1]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Hashing:</strong> One-way functions like MD5 and SHA-1 used for integrity. [cite: 1]</li>
            </ul>
            [cite_start]<p><strong>DES (Data Encryption Standard):</strong> A symmetric block cipher using a 56-bit key and 16 rounds of Feistel structure. [cite: 1]</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit3" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 3: Network Security</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>Firewalls & DMZ</h3>
            <p>A firewall controls access between networks. [cite_start]It can be a packet filter (checks headers) or a proxy (checks content). [cite: 2]</p>
            [cite_start]<p><strong>DMZ (Demilitarized Zone):</strong> A sub-network that exposes external services (like Web/Mail servers) to the internet while keeping the internal network secure. [cite: 2]</p>
            <h3>VPN & IPSec</h3>
            <ul>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>VPN:</strong> Uses public networks to create private tunnels. [cite: 2]</li>
                <li><strong>IPSec:</strong> Provides security at the Network Layer (IP). [cite_start]Modes: Transport (payload only) and Tunnel (entire packet). [cite: 2]</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit4" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 4: Digital Signatures & Authentication</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>Digital Signatures</h3>
            <p>Provides <strong>Authentication, Integrity, and Non-repudiation</strong>. [cite_start]Created by encrypting a hash of the message with the sender's Private Key. [cite: 3]</p>
            <h3>Kerberos</h3>
            <p>A trusted third-party authentication protocol developed by MIT. [cite_start]Uses "Tickets" to allow nodes to communicate over a non-secure network. [cite: 3]</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit5" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 5: Design Principles</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>Saltzer & Schroeder Principles</h3>
            <ul>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Least Privilege:</strong> Every program/user should operate with the minimum privileges necessary. [cite: 4]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Fail-Safe Defaults:</strong> Access decisions should deny by default. [cite: 4]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Economy of Mechanism:</strong> Keep security designs simple. [cite: 4]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Open Design:</strong> Security should not depend on secrecy of the design (avoid "Security by Obscurity"). [cite: 4]</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit6" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 6: Malicious Programs</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>Types of Malware</h3>
            <ul>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Virus:</strong> Code that attaches to a host program and replicates. [cite: 5]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Worm:</strong> Replicates itself across a network without needing a host file. [cite: 5]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Trojan Horse:</strong> Appears useful but contains hidden malicious code. [cite: 5]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Logic Bomb:</strong> Malware that triggers on a specific condition (e.g., a specific date). [cite: 5]</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit7" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 7: Intrusion Detection</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>IDS Models</h3>
            <ul>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Anomaly Detection:</strong> Looks for deviations from "normal" behavior (statistical baselines). prone to false positives. [cite: 6]</li>
                <li><strong>Misuse Detection:</strong> Looks for known patterns of attacks (signatures). [cite_start]Can't detect new (zero-day) attacks. [cite: 6]</li>
            </ul>
            <h3>IDS Architecture</h3>
            [cite_start]<p>Consists of <strong>Agents</strong> (collect data), <strong>Director</strong> (analyzes data), and <strong>Notifier</strong> (alerts admins). [cite: 6]</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit8" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 8: Web & Email Security</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>SSL/TLS</h3>
            <p>Protocols for secure communication over a network. TLS is the successor to SSL. [cite_start]Uses a Handshake protocol to negotiate keys. [cite: 7]</p>
            <h3>Email Security</h3>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>PGP (Pretty Good Privacy):</strong> Uses a "Web of Trust" model. [cite_start]Provides confidentiality and authentication. [cite: 7]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>S/MIME:</strong> Uses hierarchical trust (Certificate Authorities). [cite: 7]</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit9" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 9: Database Security</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>Security Controls</h3>
            <ul>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Access Control:</strong> Limiting who can see what data. [cite: 8]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Inference Control:</strong> Preventing users from guessing sensitive data from statistical aggregates. [cite: 8]</li>
                [cite_start]<li><strong>Flow Control:</strong> Ensuring data doesn't flow from high-security to low-security levels. [cite: 8]</li>
            </ul>
            [cite_start]<p><strong>Threats:</strong> Identity theft, unauthorized disclosure, and SQL injection. [cite: 7, 8]</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit10" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 10: Policy & Procedures</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>Computer Forensics</h3>
            <p>The lawful seizure, acquisition, analysis, and reporting of digital evidence. Difference from Security: Security protects systems; [cite_start]Forensics explains how they were violated. [cite: 9]</p>
            <h3>Chain of Custody</h3>
            <p>Documentation that tracks evidence from collection to court. [cite_start]Essential for legal validity. [cite: 9]</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="unit11" class="section">
        <h1>Unit 11: Issues with Internet</h1>
        <div class="content-box">
            <h3>Cyberbullying</h3>
            <p>Bullying using electronic means. Includes flaming, harassment, denigration, and exclusion. [cite_start]Distinct from traditional bullying due to anonymity and 24/7 access. [cite: 10]</p>
            <h3>Ethical Issues</h3>
            [cite_start]<p>Schools must handle copyright, privacy of student data, and staff conduct online. [cite: 10]</p>
        </div>
    </div>

    <div id="practical" class="section">
        <h1>Practical Laboratory</h1>
        <p>Complete the following tasks to demonstrate your understanding.</p>

        <div class="practical-card">
            <div class="practical-header">Lab 1: Cryptography (Unit 2)</div>
            <div class="practical-body">
                <p><strong>Task:</strong> Implement the Caesar Cipher in any programming language (Python/C/Java).</p>
                <p><strong>Requirement:</strong> The program should accept a plaintext string and a "shift" key, then output the ciphertext.</p>
                <code>Example: Input "ABC", Key 3 -> Output "DEF"</code>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="practical-card">
            <div class="practical-header">Lab 2: Network Security (Unit 3)</div>
            <div class="practical-body">
                <p><strong>Task:</strong> Configure a basic Packet Filter.</p>
                <p><strong>Requirement:</strong> If using Linux, use `iptables` to block all incoming traffic on port 23 (Telnet). If using Windows, create an inbound rule in Windows Firewall to block a specific IP address.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="practical-card">
            <div class="practical-header">Lab 3: Digital Signature (Unit 4)</div>
            <div class="practical-body">
                <p><strong>Task:</strong> Verify a File Hash.</p>
                <p><strong>Requirement:</strong> Download a file. Calculate its MD5 or SHA-256 hash using a tool (like `certutil` on Windows or `md5sum` on Linux). Compare it with the provided hash to verify integrity.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="practical-card">
            <div class="practical-header">Lab 4: Web Security (Unit 8)</div>
            <div class="practical-body">
                <p><strong>Task:</strong> Inspect SSL Certificate.</p>
                <p><strong>Requirement:</strong> Go to a secure website (e.g., google.com). Click the "Lock" icon in the address bar. View the Certificate details: Issuer, Valid From/To dates, and Public Key algorithm.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

